“You shouldn’t have gone and volunteered with those ‘progressive Christians’

You shouldn’t have read Rachel Held Evans or Rob Bell

You shouldn’t have started dating a non-Christian”

🧵
If Facebook didn’t exist I would feel no need to explain anything to people with whom I am not actively in community. #jewishconvert #deconstruction #exvangelical
These people will beg me to reconsider and come back to Jesus…even though I am happier as an almost Jew than I was probably ever in my time as a Christian.
On the other hand, I have my Facebook friends who knew me as a devout fundamentalist evangelical Christian who are shocked and upset by my conversion to Judaism…
But I have some close friends who have been with me through the process and I know they will stick by me…
And I get it. Changing up your entire religion is a HUGE deal, ESPECIALLY if you were formally an extremely devout fundamentalist evangelical Christian.
I should be working right now. Instead I am contemplating the fact that social media makes it feel as though I owe people an explanation for my conversion to Judaism.
The joy that I was supposed to be looking forward to in Christ’s resurrection was no longer there and I hadn’t recognized it until that moment.
My pastor at the time (who is honestly a great person) questioned me on this in a sort of public way, and I think I kind of in that moment realized that I wasn’t really a Christian anymore.
It’s funny, last year at the beginning of Lent I wrote my last blog as a Christian. I wrote about how the whole year of Covid felt like lent and how that felt like enough to me. 🧵
